    <id>https://doi.org/10.1287/opre.2024.0994</id>
    <title>Inventory Allocation Under the Greedy Fulfillment Policy: The (Potential) Perils of the Hindsight Approach</title>
    <updated>2026-05-22T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Stefanus Jasin, Sheng Liu, Jinglong Zhao</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;Operations Research&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Will Hindsight Approach Work Well for Multi-Location Inventory Allocation?Online retailers often decide where to place inventory before knowing which customers will arrive and in what order. A common solution is the hindsight or stochastic programming approach: allocate inventory as if future demand were known, then fulfill orders using a simple greedy rule, shipping from the cheapest available warehouse. In “Inventory Allocation under the Greedy Fulfillment Policy: The (Potential) Perils of the Hindsight Approach,” Jasin, Liu, and Zhao show that this widely used method can be deceptively optimistic. The hindsight solution is equivalent to optimizing greedy fulfillment for the most favorable arrival sequence, rather than the sequence that unfolds. The authors characterize when this optimism is harmless—identical ordering costs, no warehouse capacity constraints, and independent demands—and show that violating any of these conditions can make the hindsight allocation arbitrarily worse than the true optimum under greedy fulfillment. Their results caution retailers to evaluate allocation heuristics against the fulfillment policy actually used.</content>
    <link href="https://doi.org/10.1287/opre.2024.0994"/>
    <category term="Operations Research"/>
    <published>2026-05-22T00:00:00+00:00</published>
